# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cylinder-locomotive
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Under the Whyte notation for the classification of steam locomotives, **2-2-2** represents the wheel arrangement of two leading wheels on one axle, two powered driving wheels on one axle, and two trailing wheels on one axle.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] The wheel arrangement both provided more stability and enabled a larger firebox than the earlier 0-2-2 and 2-2-0 types.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] This wheel arrangement is sometimes described as a **Single**, although this name could be used to describe any kind of locomotive with a single pair of driving wheels.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] The 2-2-2 configuration appears to have been developed by Robert Stephenson & Company in 1834, as an enlargement of their 2-2-0 *Planet* configuration, offering more stability and a larger firebox.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] The new type became known as Stephenson's Patentee locomotive.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Adler, the first successful locomotive to operate in Germany, was a *Patentee* supplied by Robert Stephenson & Company in component form in December, 1835 was one of the earliest examples.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Other examples were exported to the Netherlands, Russia and Italy.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] By 1838 the 2-2-2 had become the standard passenger design by Robert Stephenson & Company.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Eighteen of the first nineteen locomotives ordered by Isambard Kingdom Brunel for the opening of the Great Western Railway in 1837/8 were of the 2-2-2 type.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] These included six 2-2-2 locomotives built by Charles Tayleur at his Vulcan Foundry.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Also in 1837 the successful *North Star* broad gauge locomotive was delivered to the Great Western Railway by Stephenson, becoming the first of a class of twelve locomotives by 1841.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Sharp, Roberts & Company constructed more than 600 2-2-2 locomotives between 1837 and 1857.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Ten of these supplied to the Grand Junction Railway became the basis of Alexander Allan's successful designs for the railway from 1845 (the first of which, formerly named *Columbine*, is preserved).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] John Rennie supplied 2-2-2 locomotives to the London and Croydon Railway from 1838 and the London and Brighton Railway in 1840.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Arend ("eagle") was one of the two first steam locomotives in the Netherlands, built by R.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Longridge and Company of Bedlington, Northumberland in 1839.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] The Great Western Railway continued to order both broad gauge and standard gauge locomotives on the railway, including the Firefly and Sun classes (1840–42), which were enlarged versions of North Star.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Bury, Curtis and Kennedy supplied six 2-2-2 locomotives to the Bristol and Gloucester Railway in 1844, and fourteen to the Great Southern and Western Railway in Ireland in 1848, (the last of these has been preserved at Cork Kent railway station.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] The Jenny Lind locomotive, designed by David Joy and built in 1847 for the London, Brighton and South Coast Railway by the E.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Wilson and Company of Leeds, became the basis of hundreds of similar passenger locomotives built during the 1840s and 1850s by this and other manufacturers for UK railways.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] The London and North Western Railway *Cornwall* locomotive was designed at Crewe Works as a 4-2-2 by Francis Trevithick in 1847, but was rebuilt as a 2-2-2 in 1858.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Although by the 1860s the 2-2-2 configuration was beginning to be superseded by the 2-4-0 type with better adhesion, the invention of steam sanding gave 2-2-2 singles a new lease of life, and they continued to be built until the 1890s.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Notable late examples include William Stroudley's singles of 1874–1880, William Dean's 157 class of 1878–79, and his 3001 class (1891–92), both for the Great Western Railway.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] James Holden of the Great Eastern Railway created some 2-2-2 singles in 1889 by removing the coupling rod from a 2-4-0.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] The first steam railway locomotive built in Belgium in 1835, and was built by John Cockerill under license to a design by Robert Stephenson & Company It was built for use on the first main line on the European mainland, the Brussels-Mechelen line.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] A replica was built at the workshops of Boissellerie Cognaut for the 150th anniversary of the formation of Belgium.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Two 2-2-2 locomotives were imported from Longridge and Co of Bedlington Ironworks England for the Naples–Portici railway in 1839 named Bayard and Vesuvio.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] A replica of 'Bayard is at the Naples Railway Museum.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Most of the earliest locomotives to operate in what is now Germany before the mid-1840s were 2-2-2s delivered by UK manufacturers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] However, by 1839 the type was also being built locally *see* List of Bavarian locomotives and railbuses.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] The Pegasus of 1839 was the first locomotive to be built by the Sächsische Maschinenbau-Compagnie in Chemnitz.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] August Borsig and Company manufactured Beuth in 1843 which was highly successful; its valve design became de facto standard for locomotives for decades to come.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] By 1846 he had manufactured more than a hundred similar locomotives.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Both the Leipzig-Dresden Railway and Royal Bavarian State Railways (Königlich Bayerische Staatsbahn) built several 2-2-2 classes 1841–1859.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Similarly, the Grand Duchy of Mecklenburg Friedrich-Franz Railway grouped various 2-2-2 steam locomotives procured from German manufacturers between 1848 and 1863 into its Mecklenburg I class.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] The Imperial Austrian State Railways (kaiserlich-königliche österreichische Staatsbahnen or kkStB) built two successful locomotives of this wheel arrangement in 1907.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] Similarly the Federal Railway of Austria (BBÖ) built two examples of an express tank locomotive in 1934 and 1937.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] One of last 2-2-2 tank locomotives were ordered by Latvian Railways, for local traffic.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] The locomotives Tk class were designed by German Hohenzollern, and 20 were manufactured in Germany and Latvia in 1928–1934.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] They were next seized by Soviet railways.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/2-2-2] After World War II one served in Poland as OKa1 class.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] 60163 ***Tornado*** is a 4-6-2 "Pacific" steam locomotive completed in 2008 to an original design by Arthur Peppercorn.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] At the time of completion it was the first new build steam locomotive for the British mainline since 1960, and is the only Peppercorn A1 in existence as the final locomotive of the original class was scrapped in 1966.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The A1 Steam Locomotive Trust launched the project in 1990 and was financed through fundraising initiatives, public donations, and sponsorship deals.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Construction began in 1994 at Darlington Works, England with other components manufactured elsewhere, most notably the boiler, which was constructed at Meiningen Steam Locomotive Works in Germany to meet modern EU regulations.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Following testing on the Great Central Railway in 2008, *Tornado* was granted its mainline running certificate in January 2009 and has since worked heritage and mainline trains across Britain.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In 2017, *Tornado* became the first steam locomotive to officially reach 100 mph (160 km/h) on British tracks in over 50 years.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] It was withdrawn in 2021 for an extensive overhaul and returned to service in 2024.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The success of *Tornado* led the A1 Steam Locomotive Trust to launch a new build project for another LNER locomotive, P2 Class 2007 *Prince of Wales*.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In 1990, the charitable A1 Steam Locomotive Trust was founded with the intention of building a new LNER Peppercorn Class A1 steam locomotive as the 50th member of its class.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The original 49 Peppercorn A1s were built in 1948 and 1949 at Doncaster and Darlington Works at £16,000 each.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] They were initially ordered for operation on the London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) to a design by its chief mechanical engineer Arthur Peppercorn, but were delivered after the company had been nationalised and became British Railways.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The Peppercorn A1s ran services on the East Coast Main Line until the last one was scrapped in September 1966 after a comparatively short service of 15 years.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The name *Tornado* was chosen in honour of the Royal Air Force Panavia Tornado air crews flying at the time in the Gulf War.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The honour of choosing the name was given to a £50,000 sponsor of the project.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In January 1995, officers of the Royal Air Force presented the *Tornado* nameplates to the trust at Tyseley Locomotive Works at a frame laying ceremony.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The smokebox door carries the identification plate of 51 A, the code for Darlington shed, and the cab side carries a builder's plate No.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The front buffer beam carries the designation A1.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 19 February 2009, *Tornado* was officially named by the Prince of Wales, accompanied by the Duchess of Cornwall and Dorothy Mather, Peppercorn's widow, at York railway station.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The ceremony is marked by a plaque located below the nameplate.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] *Tornado* then pulled the Royal Train to Leeds.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On hearing of the project in October 1991, Argentine locomotive engineer Livio Dante Porta contacted the trust, hailing the project as the start of a "renaissance of steam technology".
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In 1992, he submitted *A proposal for the Tornado project* in which he presented to the trust several design improvements that could be made to *Tornado* that, while preserving the outer form, would make it a second-generation steam locomotive.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Ironically, in 2003, it was decided to make *Tornado* oil-fired for cost and operational reasons, following earlier dual-fuelled coal-and-oil-fired proposals in 1998, when boiler design commenced.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] This was later abandoned in favour of the original design of coal firing, due to the large increase in global fossil fuel prices, and to save the certification costs of this design difference.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] There were no general arrangement drawings of a Peppercorn A1, so rough engineering dimensions for *Tornado* were obtained from measuring Peppercorn Class A2 60532 *Blue Peter* at the National Railway Museum (NRM).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Many of the drawings originally used at Doncaster Works for the Peppercorn A1's had been preserved at the NRM, and a team of volunteers spent three days collating these in 1991.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The original drawings were India ink drawings on linen which had to be scanned into a computer aided design (CAD) software program as the microfilm copies at the NRM were not suitable for manufacturing purposes, and direct dyeline copies could not be made.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] 95% of the original drawings were found, with 1,100 scanned by 1993, and a further 140 in 2001.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A few poor quality originals required re-drawing.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Updated specifications were required to be drawn up to account for out-of-date material specifications and drawing notes whose original meaning could not be determined.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Other design details were also obtained through interviews with Peppercorn's former assistant, J.F.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] With advances in manufacturing, *Tornado's* 48-foot-6-inch (14.78 m) long steel plates were electronically cut from one piece of steel, as opposed to the original Peppercorn A1s, which had two-piece frames riveted together.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] These are probably the most accurate steam locomotive frames ever produced.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Despite their higher costs, roller bearings were used owing to the reliability they had demonstrated after a trial on some of the original engines.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] This caused an unforeseen problem in 2003 since the modifications made to the tender in the original fitting of roller bearings as an experiment to some Peppercorn A1s had not been properly drawn for the Cartazzi axle of the trailing wheels.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A 1-inch (25 mm) reduction in height from the original 13-foot-1-inch (3.99 m) height was required by the Network Rail regulations, and was achieved by a redesign of the dome and safety valve mountings on the boiler, and by reprofiling of the cab roof and chimney.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Testing was planned to occur with a lipped chimney, and on receipt of the first full livery, *Tornado* was fitted with an authentic rimless chimney, described as the original non-capped version.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The fluted chimney was still not fitted at the time of its LNER Apple Green livery launch on 13 December 2008, due to it still being machined at the manufacturer.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] It was completed and fitted in time for the inaugural main line passenger run.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The chimney was also fitted with a spark arrestor.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] *Tornado* has two whistles: a standard LNER "teapot" whistle on the cab front and an ex-LNER chime whistle from LNER Class A4 4482 *Golden Eagle* behind the right-hand deflector.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Consideration of the boiler began in late 1998.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] No standard gauge boiler had been built in Britain for such a large express locomotive since the 1960s, and it was required to be based on the original LNER design but meet modern safety standards.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Design changes included the cheaper modern-day fabrication method of a welded, rather than riveted, firebox and boiler tubing; the use of steel, rather than copper, for the firebox; and the aforementioned height reduction for Network Rail regulations.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In early 2002, the Deutsche Bahn's Meiningen Steam Locomotive Works in Germany was identified as a suitable supplier.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] It possessed the required knowledge as main line steam operation had continued in East Germany until the mid-1980s, 70% of its work still involved steam, and it still possessed the powerful plate roller machines.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The trust did not have sufficient funding to place the order until January 2005.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 16 July 2006, the boiler arrived by sea and was unloaded at Darlington with a 200-ton crane, having taken just nine months to build.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The fitting of the 21-ton firebox and boiler unit to the wheeled locomotive frame was said to have been a perfect fit, requiring no grinding at all, a tribute to the accuracy of the design and construction at Meiningen.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The fitting was not without incident though, as the extra weight caused some compaction of the trackbed, and assistance was required to move the locomotive back into the works, by a combination of being winched, towed by a forklift truck and pushed with Land Rovers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A further modification to the boiler design has been the use of hollow stays which support and separate the outer boiler and inner firebox.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The hollow stays act as an indicator of any cracks in the otherwise inaccessible stays, such cracks being revealed by water leaks.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Leaks have in fact been detected and have led to the locomotive being unavailable for service.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In 1991, a preference for a "Doncaster pattern" riveted tender was expressed as per the original Peppercorn A1s.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The redundant tender of LNER Class A3 4472 *Flying Scotsman* was acquired, although later returned unused, allowing *Tornado* to remain a completely originally manufactured locomotive.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] By 2002, it was agreed that a flush sided (all welded) boiler and tender was appropriate for a Darlington-built Peppercorn A1, making construction and maintenance easier.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The tender was redesigned internally, removing the water scoop, increasing the water capacity from 5,000 to 6,000 gallons, and reducing coal capacity from 9 to 7.5 tons.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In 2003 the need for a second tender for *Tornado* was discounted.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The motion components alone cost £150,000, taking £50,000 to forge (and requiring three years to complete) and £100,000 to machine.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The wheelset was the first mainline steam locomotive wheelset to be manufactured in Britain since 1960, and took five years and nine suppliers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The wheels were so smooth that the complete locomotive could easily be pushed out of the works by human power alone, as seen when the locomotive was moved outside in preparation for its first steam-powered moves.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] If the locomotive were to be suspended, the entire wheel and motion arrangement could be turned by hand.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In March 1997 *Tornado*, as a completed frame and inside cylinder, was displayed in the Great Hall at the National Railway Museum for several weeks.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] It returned to Tyseley to await completion of Darlington Works.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The elements of *Tornado* were brought together with the opening of the works in 1997, and the opening ceremony saw the unveiled locomotive, now consisting of the frame with its three cylinders and cab attached.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Early 1998 saw the smokebox construction started and the tyres fitted and by 1999, forging of the motion components had started with the first delivery of components commencing in January 2000.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] By September 1999, the last wheel had been pressed onto the wheelset, which was delivered to Darlington by July 2000.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] By January 2000, the front bogie had been assembled.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] With the fitting of these parts, the mounting of the frame onto the wheelset, and fitting of the smokebox, by the end of 2000, the most visible missing parts of *Tornado* were the boiler and tender.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Post-2000, assembly and setting of the motion proceeded, and attention turned to the design of the boiler; a £250,000 appeal was launched.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] *Tornado* became a rolling chassis by October 2002, and achieved the first synchronous movement of the motion and all wheels in August 2004.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] 2005 saw construction of the boiler in Germany, with construction begun on 16 October, and completed in time for delivery on 16 July 2006.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] By June 2007 *Tornado's* internal construction was sufficiently complete to allow fitting of the boiler to the frame, using a 100-ton crane.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The most complex casting, the superheater header, was started in 2007, and after defeating two foundries the complex shape was cast by a third supplier.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Owing to space constraints at Darlington works, the *Tornado* tender frames and body were built off-site, with the body being significantly built locally in Darlington.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The tender wheelsets were assembled by an East Lancs Railway-based company.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The tender frame and wheelset were united by December 2007, and the tank attached to it by February 2008.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] From its construction until final testing was completed, *Tornado* sported a grey coloured undercoat as a precaution in case the boiler cladding had to be removed.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The livery was described as "works grey" in a "satin finish".
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] While in this undercoat, *Tornado* wore the web address of the A1 Trust on the side of the tender and the mark RA9 on the locomotive cab, denoting its route availability.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A computer simulation was used to assist in the setting up of the valves and motion.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The boiler safety valves were tested on LNER Class A4 60009 *Union of South Africa* at the Severn Valley Railway before their delivery to Meiningen for fitting to *Tornado*.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The boiler was hydraulically tested at the manufacturer's factory at one-and-a-half times working pressure and was passed safe.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 11 January 2008, the boiler passed its first steam test in a series of tests carried out by an external boiler inspector.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] For the test, the fire was lit and the boiler was allowed to warm up for over 48 hours before being then taken up to 260 psi (1,800 kPa), just over the maximum working pressure, with the safety valves set to the correct pressure.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The boiler was noted by the inspector to be a very rapid one, boding well for use on the mainline, and noted *Tornado* exhibited no leaks of any kind, in contrast to heritage locomotive restorations.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The tender body was not yet finished by this time so the test was conducted using a water bowser.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The boiler created steam so efficiently that the water supply was being used faster than it could be replenished by the mains water supply to the works.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] To complete the test and not prematurely damp down the fire, an emergency call for water was made to the local fire brigade, who responded with a fire tender to supply more water.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] This was sensationally but inaccurately reported in one local newspaper as "fire brigade called to prevent boiler explosion".
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Low speed trials of *Tornado* as a live steam locomotive first occurred on the 500-foot (150 m) long track at Darlington Works.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] After a series of private tests, *Tornado* made its first in-steam moves on 29 July 2008, followed by its official launch on 1 August, moving up and down the test siding in front of the press.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The 1 August launch coincided with the 40th anniversary of the end of steam on British Railways on 4 August 1968, and the 60th anniversary of the entry into traffic of the first Peppercorn A1 class locomotive, No.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 7 August, *Tornado* was entered onto Total Operations Processing System (TOPS), a computer system used in the UK for managing locomotives and rolling stock.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Although the painted number is 60163, *Tornado* is designated 98863 on the British main line in TOPS, where "98" describes a steam engine, the "8" stems from the power classification of 8P, and "63" comes from its 60163 number.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] From Darlington Works, *Tornado* was moved by road on two articulated lorries to the Great Central Railway on 19 August, where it performed mileage accumulation and testing before hauling its first passenger trains.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] After three days, *Tornado* had completed its first non-stop mile run and had hauled empty coaches.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Following HM Railway Inspectorate (HMRI) recommendations, it went on to haul empty trains at speeds up to 60 mph (97 km/h) and with a load of up to around 500 tons.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] One load test involved a rake of 11 coaches and a Class 45 diesel locomotive, and another saw it achieve 2,000 drawbar horsepower.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 10 September *Tornado* was officially timed for the first time, hauling 518 tons up the 1-in-176 gradient south from Rothley station.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] For the GCR's Day Out with Thomas event during the Summer Bank Holiday weekend, *Tornado* wore a small Thomas face for light runs.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 21 October 2008, *Tornado* arrived at the National Railway Museum in York, and was first put on display in the Great Hall for several days, where it was placed on its central turntable for the annual railway industry dinner on 23 October.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] *Tornado* then remained operationally based at the NRM behind the scenes for final preparations and testing on the main line, reaching speeds of up to 75 mph (121 km/h), before an expected main line debut in February 2009.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The acceptance testing based at York was conducted by DB Schenker.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Three test runs were planned for 4, 6 and 18 November 2008, involving out and back journeys from York in the evenings.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The first was to Scarborough, a round trip of 84 miles (135 km), with a support coach only.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The second was a 142-mile (229 km) round trip to Barrow Hill, with *Tornado* hauling a 500-ton load of 12 coaches and a Class 67 diesel at up to 60 mph (97 km/h).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The third run was a 176-mile (283 km) trip to Newcastle with a rake of empty coaches that reached 75 mph (121 km/h) On this run, the web address on the side of the tender was replaced with the National Express logo.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Following the test runs, *Tornado* received its first full livery at the NRM's paint shop where it was painted in LNER Apple Green with "British Railways" on the tender, as worn by the first original 30 Peppercorn A1s.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The livery was applied traditionally, brush painted by hand.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] It was unveiled on the turntable at the NRM's Great Hall on 13 December 2008 at a launch ceremony attended by 500 supporters of the A1 Trust.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A dynamometer car from the North Eastern Railway was attached.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Due to time constraints, detailing was completed on one side only at the time of the launch, after which *Tornado* returned to the paint shop before going back on display for the Christmas period.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 11 January 2009, *Tornado* left the NRM for preparations for its mainline passenger debut.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A final test run was completed with a single support coach from York to Leeds and back, on 28 January.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] As a new build locomotive, *Tornado*'s certification was more complex in comparison to a restored one and required liaison with Network Rail, HMRI, and a vehicle acceptance body, with the origin of all construction materials needing to be documented and every aspect of the manufacture recorded.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Following manufacture, a technical file and Notified Body certificate was obtained on completion of a manufacturing and maintenance procedures review which was managed by DeltaRail Group Ltd.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In liaison with Network Rail, a route acceptance strategy was agreed upon and approval for *Tornado* to enter service was granted by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] This was completed in two stages, approval under the Railway and Other Transport Systems regulations, for use on the GCR and other preserved lines, and then as an "interoperable" locomotive for use on the mainline network.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] As well as standard tests, as technically a new design of locomotive, *Tornado* was required to undergo specific extra tests set by the Network Rail Safety Review Panel to examine ride quality and track force, in order to assess the effect the locomotive would have on the main line track.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Measurements were taken on board by 21 sensors measuring pitch and roll, and acceleration and deceleration.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Measurements were also taken through the use of track-side sensors measuring side forces exerted on the rails, augmented with freeze-frame footage of the position of the wheels as they passed.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The results were compared with control readings taken at the same site using BR Standard Class 7 70013 *Oliver Cromwell* two weeks later.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The preliminary results were described as producing "no untoward signals".
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] It was stated that while a 10% overspeed is allowed (and may be required) in such new equipment test runs (A4 Class 4464 *Bittern* reached 83 mph (134 km/h) in 2007), *Tornado* had not been planned or authorised to do so on this test.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] It was suggested that the discrepancy might have been down to the equipment on the Class 67 having had its gearing altered but not having been recalibrated.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] It was expected that the first phase of main line operational running would be limited to trips of 200 to 250 miles (400 km).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The expanded water capacity of the tender allows legs of over 100 miles (160 km) between water stops, 25 miles (40 km) further than the original Peppercorn A1s.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] To assist in passenger operation, in 2008 the Trust purchased a Mark 1 composite corridor support coach which entered traffic in 2013.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] *Tornado* has a route availability of 9.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] From 2009, *Tornado* began to recoup the estimated £800,000 debt from the project.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 31 January 2009, *Tornado* completed its first passenger trip on the British mainline, hauling *The Peppercorn Pioneer* in a return trip from York to Newcastle via Darlington and Durham.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The route was a replica of the last tour hauled by the last surviving original Peppercorn A1, 60145 *St Mungo*, 42 years earlier.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The same journey was planned for 1 February, but on advice from the British Transport Police and Network Rail, the second trip ran from Doncaster to Durham with *Tornado* hauling only part of the return leg.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Both trips carried 500 passengers, and were organised for covenanters only.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] This was followed by its first mainline train available to the wider public on 7 February, hauling the A1 Trust's own *The Talisman* from Darlington to London King's Cross.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Its first departures out of London were to be two circular tours named the *Cathedrals Express* from Victoria station on 14 February, but the first tour was subsequently changed and left from Waterloo.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In April 2009, *Tornado* appeared at the LNER-themed event at Barrow Hill Roundhouse where it featured alongside Peppercorn A2 Class 60532 *Blue Peter* and Class A4s 4498 *Sir Nigel Gresley* and 4488 *Union of South Africa*.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] *Blue Peter* was repainted in LNER Apple Green livery for display alongside *Tornado*, and their meeting re-created a scene not witnessed for nearly 50 years.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] *Tornado* also posed alongside narrow gauge locomotive No.7 *Typhoon* of the Romney, Hythe and Dymchurch Railway, recreating an LNER publicity shot held previously with *Typhoon* and LNER Class A3 4472 *Flying Scotsman*.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 21 December, *Tornado* rescued about 100 people who were stranded by bad weather at London Victoria.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A number of electric trains, which pick up their power from the third rail, were unable to run because of snow and ice on the line.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] *Tornado* was to haul a *Cathedrals Express* lunchtime special, but some booked passengers were unable to get there due to the conditions, leaving spare seats.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The train's operators decided to offer them to commuters whose trains had been cancelled.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] *Tornado* also had an evening *Cathedrals Express* dining train, and the same offer was again made.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The A1 Trust promised to paint *Tornado* in all four liveries that the original Peppercorn A1s had worn during its first period of operation with its first 10-year boiler certificate.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In early 2011, following remedial attention to its boiler in Germany, *Tornado* unveiled in BR Brunswick Green, which the original class wore in the 1950s.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The "British Railways" on the tender was replaced with an emblem and crest.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] This lasted until its withdrawal for winter maintenance in late 2012, during which it was repainted in BR Express Passenger Blue, the second livery carried by the original class.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In 2015, following an intermediate overhaul, *Tornado* returned to service in its original LNER Apple Green.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] This lasted until mid-2020 when it was painted in BR Brunswick Green in celebration of the A1 Trust's 30th anniversary, which lasted until its withdrawal for overhaul in 2022, where it was painted back into Apple Green.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The original Peppercorn A1s were easily capable of reaching 100 mph (160 km/h) and in 2004, approval was sought for *Tornado* to achieve regular 90 mph (140 km/h) operation.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] While older preserved steam locomotives are subject to speed restrictions due to age, approval for 90 mph (140 km/h) running was possible for *Tornado* due to its new condition.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In January 2009, having gained approval for running at 75 mph (121 km/h), discussions took place about testing *Tornado* to higher speeds.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In the early hours of 12 April 2017, *Tornado* achieved 100 mph (160 km/h) during a test run on the East Coast Main Line, becoming the first steam locomotive to reach the speed on the British mainline since 1968.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A programme on the planning, build-up and fulfilment of the project was captured in the BBC film *Tornado: The 100mph Steam Engine*.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In September 2011, *Tornado* set a new record for the longest single day trip in Britain by a steam locomotive since the 1960s, pulling *The Caledonian Tornado* from Crewe to Glasgow and back for over 530 miles (850 km).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In 2013, it hauled the first steam-hauled service from London Victoria to Sheffield Park via East Grinstead and the Bluebell Railway since 1963.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In 2017, *Tornado* was used by Northern Rail on scheduled public timetabled services between Appleby and Skipton prior to the reopening of the Settle–Carlisle line, which had been closed for a year because of a landslip.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 14 April 2018, while running at 90 mph (140 km/h) south of Peterborough on *The Ebor Flyer* from London King's Cross to York, the locomotive's inside motion failed.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The subsequent repairs and re-testing took several months to complete.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In November 2021, *Tornado* was withdrawn from mainline service after a number of tender wheel flats caused by slippage from falling leaves were detected.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Following an appearance at the Great Central Railway in January 2022, the locomotive moved to Loughborough for dismantling and major overhaul.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] It was to be complete in July, but delays caused by the COVID-19 pandemic while the boiler was being restored at Meiningen Works in Germany, and additional work needed on the driving wheels and tyres, led to its completion date pushed back to the spring of 2023.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] However problems with the boiler further delayed completion of the work.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The overhaul included the installation of European Rail Traffic Management System (ERTMS) in-cab signalling equipment.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] After completion of overhaul, in May 2024, *Tornado* was moved to the Great Central Railway to undergo testing under steam as well as installing European Train Control System (ETCS) signalling equipment.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In March 2025, *Tornado* completed testing to allow the locomotive to run on the main line.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In mid-April 2025 *Tornado* was tested running under ETCS in-cab signalling between Shrewsbury and Welshpool on the Cambrian Line in Wales.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In September 1996, the concept of dedicated covenants was launched.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Now renamed dedicated donations, these were one-off payments of £25 to £25,000 to sponsor a particular part.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] As with regular covenantors, dedicated donors receive recognition, and an engineering drawing of the component they sponsored.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In October 1999 a £250,000 appeal was launched to fund the boiler, whose absence was noticeable with *Tornado* then comprising a wheeled frame with completed cab and smokebox.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] As *Tornado* began to look like a locomotive with the mating of the frame with the wheelset in the autumn of 2000, fundraising progress increased, breaking previous records by recruiting 100 new covenantors in two months.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] By 2005, the trust had raised over £1.5m.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Completion of the boiler was achieved through a half-million pound bond issue.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Following securing of the boiler funds, the last major part, the tender, was achieved with a £200,000 single sponsor donation.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] By May 2008, £2.5m had been raised and spent, and the gap to the required £3m had been raised to complete *Tornado*.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] However, due to the Chinese economic boom causing raw materials cost increases, together with increased certification costs, a further £50,000 appeal had to be launched if main line running was to be achieved by September.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] By the end of September 2008, the Trust still needed to raise £66,000 to pay for tests and trials to allow main line operation.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] While at the GCR, the project costs were running at the rate of £10,000 a month, rising to "six-figure bills" for certification in the months up to January 2009.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Launched in 2004, the Trust's half-million pound bond issue offered 4% returns, but in January 2009 £100,000 worth of these bonds remained unsubscribed.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In 1994 the A1 trust gained its first major sponsor, William Cook Cast Products.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In 1997, Great North Eastern Railway (GNER), the then operator on the East Coast Main Line, became a sponsor, and decorated Darlington station for the event, as well as offering free travel for trust workers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The trust gained Rolls-Royce as a sponsor in spring 1998.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The trust's principal sponsor is William Cook Cast Products, which initially cast the driving wheels on "very advantageous terms", and later assisted with all the wheels and almost all other steel castings.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] As with GNER, *Tornado's* links to the East Coast Main Line brought with it support from the next incumbent operator, National Express East Coast, with sponsorship of the third main line test run to Newcastle.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Significant savings were made through industrial sponsorship; by 1998 this was keeping costs at 40% of normal.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Some components, such as the smokebox door, were even obtained free of charge.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Cost savings of a third of the original manufacturing costs were possible in some cases where the building of one locomotive allowed for cheaper construction methods, such as using one-off polystyrene casting patterns.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Several other events and fund-raising drives have assisted in funding the project, including a Land's End to John O'Groats bike ride.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The Trust also received proceeds from the sale of limited edition models of *Tornado* in works grey livery.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A new book on the story of Tornado called *Tornado 21st Century Steam*, written by *The Guardian's* Jonathan Glancey, was released on 15 October 2010.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A BBC film crew filmed the project at certain points on the journey, up to and including the arrival and operation of *Tornado* running at the GCR.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The resulting film was used to make a 30-minute documentary film, *Absolutely Chuffed: The Men Who Built a Steam Engine*.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] It was first broadcast on BBC Four on 16 October 2008, as part of their Golden Age of Steam season.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The film was released on Region 2 DVD on 28 December 2009 with unseen material and DVD extras.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] On 25 April 2009, *Tornado* hauled a 10-coach *Cathedrals Express* charter from London King's Cross to Edinburgh Waverley.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] This private train was filmed by the BBC for a retro *Top Gear* Race, in which Jeremy Clarkson on the train raced James May in a Jaguar XK120 and Richard Hammond on a Vincent Black Shadow motorbike.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] *Tornado* was booked to complete the 390.2-mile (628.0 km) journey in 8 hours 2 minutes, without any passenger stops at stations, but with four water stops en route at Grantham, York, Tyne Yard and Berwick, totalling 95 minutes booked stoppage time.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Because motorways did not exist in 1949 (the first not being built until 1959) May and Hammond were restricted to using A-roads.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] In a close finish, *Tornado* came second behind the Jaguar, with a difference of only about ten minutes between them.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The train was formed from the maroon support coach and a uniform rake of nine *Royal Scot* blood and custard coaches.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The race featured in the first episode of the show's 13th series, airing on 21 June 2009.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] 60163 *Tornado*, as well as LMS Hughes Crab no.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] A "very limited edition" customised model from The Model Centre (TMC), based on the Bachmann OO scale model in grey livery helped raise funds for the project.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Another grey works *Tornado* was to be made by TMC but with National Express on its tender from its 18 November main line test run.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Bachmann released a *Tornado* model in BR Apple Green livery just before Christmas 2009.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] This is particularly evident on the tender, which features the enlarged water capacity and reduced coal storage of *Tornado* as compared to the original A1 locomotives.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The model proved extremely popular, to the extent that 10 weeks after going on sale Bachmann stocks were exhausted and more models had to be ordered.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Since 2011, Hornby Railways have produced a model of *Tornado* in 00 gauge.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Graham Farish have produced a model in N scale.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] For their 2013/2014 range, Bachmann released an Express Passenger Blue model of *Tornado* which is a standard repaint and slightly modified Peppercorn A1 Pacific.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Darstaed Models are to manufacture an O scale model of *Tornado* using tinplate.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] The model will feature traditional three-rail electric pick up.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/60163-tornado] Accucraft (UK) make a live steam model of *Tornado* in gauge 1.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A **high pressure watertube boiler** (also spelled *water-tube* and *water tube*) is a type of boiler in which water circulates in tubes heated externally by fire.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Fuel is burned inside the furnace, creating hot gas which boils water in the steam-generating tubes.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In smaller boilers, additional generating tubes are separate in the furnace, while larger utility boilers rely on the water-filled tubes that make up the walls of the furnace to generate steam.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The heated water/steam mixture then rises into the steam drum.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Here, saturated steam is drawn off the top of the drum.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In some services, the steam passes through tubes in the hot gas path (a superheater) to become superheated.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Superheated steam is a dry gas and therefore is typically used to drive turbines, since water droplets can severely damage turbine blades.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Saturated water at the bottom of the steam drum returns to the lower drum via large-bore 'downcomer tubes', where it pre-heats the feedwater supply.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] (In large utility boilers, the feedwater is supplied to the steam drum and the downcomers supply water to the bottom of the waterwalls).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] To increase economy of the boiler, exhaust gases are also used to pre-heat combustion air blown into the burners, and to warm the feedwater supply in an economizer.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Such watertube boilers in thermal power stations are also called *steam generating units*.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The older fire-tube boiler design, in which the water surrounds the heat source and gases from combustion pass through tubes within the water space, is typically a much weaker structure and is rarely used for pressures above 2.4 MPa (350 psi).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A significant advantage of the watertube boiler is that there is less chance of a catastrophic failure: there is not a large volume of water in the boiler nor are there large mechanical elements subject to failure.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A water-tube boiler was patented by Blakey of England in 1766 and was made by Dallery of France in 1780.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "The ability of watertube boilers to be designed without the use of excessively large and thick-walled pressure vessels makes these boilers particularly attractive in applications that require dry, high-pressure, high-energy steam, including steam turbine power generation".
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Besides, they are frequently employed in power generation plants where large quantities of steam (ranging up to 500 kg/s) having high pressures i.e. approximately 16 megapascals (160 bar) and high temperatures reaching up to 550 °C are generally required.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] For example, the Ivanpah solar-power station uses two Rentech Type-D watertube boilers for plant warmup, and when operating as a fossil-fueled power station.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Modern boilers for power generation are almost entirely water-tube designs, owing to their ability to operate at higher pressures.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Where process steam is required for heating or as a chemical component, then there is still a small niche for fire-tube boilers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One notable exception is in typical nuclear-power stations (Pressurized Water Reactors), where the steam generators are generally configured similar to firetube boiler designs.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In these applications the hot gas path through the "Firetubes" actually carries the very hot/high pressure primary coolant from the reactor, and steam is generated on the external surface of the tubes.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Their ability to work at higher pressures has led to marine boilers being almost entirely watertube.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This change began around 1900, and traced the adoption of turbines for propulsion rather than reciprocating (i.e. piston) engines – although watertube boilers were also used with reciprocating engines, and firetube boilers were also used in many marine turbine applications.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There has been no significant adoption of water-tube boilers for railway locomotives.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A handful of experimental designs were produced, but none of them were successful or led to their widespread use.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most water-tube railway locomotives, especially in Europe, used the Schmidt system.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most were compounds, and a few uniflows.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Norfolk and Western Railway's *Jawn Henry* was an exception, because it used a steam turbine combined with an electric transmission.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Not successful and re-boilered with a conventional boiler.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A slightly more successful adoption was the use of hybrid water-tube/fire-tube systems.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] As the hottest part of a locomotive boiler is the firebox, it was an effective design to use water-tubes here and a conventional fire-tube boiler as an economiser (i.e. pre-heater) in the usual position.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One famous example of this was the USA Baldwin 4-10-2 No.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Built as a compound with a boiler pressure of 2,400 kilopascals (350 psi) it successfully covered over 160,000 kilometres (100,000 mi) in service.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] After a year however, it became clear that any improvements were overwhelmed by the extra costs, and it was retired as a museum display at the Franklin Institute in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A series of twelve experimental locomotives were constructed at the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad's Mt.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Clare shops under the supervision of George H.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Emerson, but none of them were replicated in any numbers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The only water-tube locomotive boiler used in any large numbers was the Brotan boiler, invented by Johann Brotan in Austria in 1902 and found sparsely throughout Europe, although Hungary had around 1,000 in service.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Like the Baldwin 60000, it combined a water-tube firebox with a fire-tube barrel.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Brotan's original characteristic was a long steam drum running *above* the main barrel, resembling a Flaman boiler in appearance.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] While traction engines were usually built with locomotive boiler as its frame, other types of steam road vehicles such as lorries and cars used a wide range of different boiler types.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Road transport pioneers Goldsworthy Gurney and Walter Hancock both used water-tube boilers in their steam carriages around 1830.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most undertype wagons used water-tube boilers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many manufacturers used variants of the vertical cross-tube boiler, including Atkinson, Clayton, Garrett and Sentinel.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Other types include the Clarkson 'thimble tube' and the Foden O-type wagon's pistol-shaped boiler.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Steam fire-engine makers such as Merryweather usually used water-tube boilers for their rapid steam-raising capacity.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many steam cars used water-tube boilers, and the Bolsover Express company even made a water-tube replacement for the Stanley Steamer fire-tube boiler.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The 'D-type' is the most common type of small- to medium-sized boilers, similar to the one shown in the schematic diagram.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It is used in both stationary and marine applications.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It consists of a large steam drum vertically connected to a smaller water drum (a.k.a.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "mud drum") via multiple steam-generating tubes.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These drums and tubes as well as the oil-fired burner are enclosed by water-walls - additional water-filled tubes spaced close together so as to prevent gas flow between them.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These water wall tubes are connected to both the steam and water drums, so that they act as a combination of preheaters and downcomers as well as decreasing heat loss to the boiler shell.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The M-type boilers were used in many US World War II warships including hundreds of *Fletcher*-class destroyers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Three sets of tubes form the shape of an M, and create a separately fired superheater that allows better superheat temperature control.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In addition to the mud drum shown on a D-type boiler, an M-type has a water-screen header and a waterwall header at the bottom of the two additional rows of vertical tubes and downcomers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The *low water content* boiler has a lower and upper header connected by watertubes that are directly impinged upon from the burner.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This is a "furnace-less" boiler that can generate steam and react quickly to changes in load.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Designed by the American firm of Babcock & Wilcox, this type has a single drum, with feedwater drawn from the bottom of the drum into a header that supplies inclined water-tubes.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The watertubes supply steam back into the top of the drum.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Furnaces are located below the tubes and drum.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This type of boiler was used by the Royal Navy's *Leander*-class frigates and in United States Navy New Orleans-class cruisers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Stirling boiler has near-vertical, almost-straight watertubes that zig-zag between a number of steam and water drums.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Usually there are three banks of tubes in a "four drum" layout, but certain applications use variations designed with a different number of drums and banks.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] They are mainly used as stationary boilers, owing to their large size, although the large grate area does also encourage their ability to burn a wide range of fuels.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Originally coal-fired in power stations, they also became widespread in industries that produced combustible waste and required process steam.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Paper pulp mills could burn waste bark, sugar refineries their bagasse waste.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Named after its designers, the then Poplar-based Yarrow Shipbuilders, this type of three-drum boiler has three drums in a delta formation connected by watertubes.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The drums are linked by straight watertubes, allowing easy tube-cleaning.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This does, however, mean that the tubes enter the drums at varying angles, a more difficult joint to caulk.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Outside the firebox, a pair of cold-leg pipes between each drum act as downcomers.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Due to its three drums, the Yarrow boiler has a greater water capacity.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Hence, this type is usually used in older marine boiler applications.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Its compact size made it attractive for use in transportable power generation units during World War II.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In order to make it transportable, the boiler and its auxiliary equipment (fuel oil heating, pumping units, fans etc.), turbines, and condensers were mounted on wagons to be transported by rail.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The White-Forster type is similar to the Yarrow, but with tubes that are gradually curved.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This makes their entry into the drums perpendicular, thus simpler to make a reliable seal.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Thornycroft & Company, the Thornycroft type features a single steam drum with two sets of watertubes either side of the furnace.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These tubes, especially the central set, have sharp curves.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Apart from obvious difficulties in cleaning them, this may also give rise to bending forces as the tubes warm up, tending to pull them loose from the tubeplate and creating a leak.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There are two furnaces, venting into a common exhaust, giving the boiler a wide base tapering profile.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In a forced circulation boiler, a pump is added to speed up the flow of water through the tubes.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] After about 1910, the **Baker valve gear** was the main competitor to Walschaerts valve gear for steam locomotives in the United States.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] Strictly speaking it was not a valve gear but a variable expansion mechanism adapted to the Walschaerts layout replacing the expansion link and sliding die block.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] The Baker arrangement used more pivot bearings or *pin joints*, but avoided the die slip inherent to the expansion link, with the aim of lessening wear and the need for service; it could also facilitate longer valve travel.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] In the early 1900s there were many efforts to create a new valve gear to replace the by-then-standard Walschaerts valve gear.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] In the United States the Young, Southern, Caprotti and Franklin patterns were used on a few classes, but only the Baker pattern won more than limited acceptance.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] Baker Company, of Swanton, Ohio; a builder of steam traction engines.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] The idea came from an employee called Gifford but was developed by the Baker company with the first patents being issued in 1903 and with patents issued through at least November, 1912.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] The Baker Locomotive Valve Gear was produced by the Pilliod Co. of Swanton, Ohio.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] Subsequent versions were produced up to the end of steam service.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] It was particularly popular on the Norfolk and Western Railway, and almost all later N&W engines used it.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] Other extensive users included the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway, the Nickel Plate Road, the New York Central Railroad and the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] There was always debate about the advantages of Baker gear, the main criticism being the number of pin joints and possible lost motion.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] While popular with railroads on the east, western states tended to continue with the Walschaerts pattern.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] In Britain, Baker gear was popular amongst model engineers but in full-size practice the length of the yoke and the width of the assembly may have been difficult to accommodate within the restricted loading gauge.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] Other locomotives to use Baker valve gear were the New Zealand Railways J class, Ja class, Jb class, some Ka class, and the South Australian Railways 620 class.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] The Baker valve gear replaces the expansion link of the Walschaerts gear with an assembly of levers and links which produces the same effect of allowing continuous variation valve travel.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] The remainder of the gear is the same, so that the return crank and combination lever take the same form, although the proportions are usually modified.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] The Pilliod Co. sold the gear as a single assembly which was mounted on the frame in the location ordinarily occupied by the Walschaerts expansion link.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] The parts were arranged so that when the yoke was centered, the connection of the main link to the bellcrank was in a line with the two pivots on the yoke.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] At this point, the back and forth motion of the lower end of the main link left the top relatively motionless as main link swung back and forth on the swing links.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] In forward motion, the yoke was pushed forward, so that its upper pivot was in front of the bell crank-main link connection.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] Moving the eccentric arm back and forth lowered and raised the top of the main link.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] This motion was translated by the bellcrank into back and forth motion of the radius rod.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/baker-valve-gear] The angle of the yoke controlled the relative motion, and therefore the cutoff; tilting the yoke backwards reversed the motion of the radius rod.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] A **bash valve** is a valve within a piston engine, used to control the admission of the working fluid.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] They are directly actuated valves, operated by contact between the piston and the valve tip.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Bash valves have the advantage of great simplicity, for manufacture and operation.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Their disadvantages are that their opening and closing times are relatively crudely controlled, compared to other types of valve gear.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The valve is usually constructed as a circular poppet valve with a conical seat, inserted into the cylinder from the outside.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] A protrusion on the inside is hit by the piston as it approaches top dead centre, forcing the valve open.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Bash valves are usually held closed by the pressure of fluid in the reservoir behind them.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] There may be a light spring to assist closing when the reservoir is empty.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] For this reason they are used as inlet valves, not exhaust.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] An exhaust bash valve would have the cylinder pressure and the piston actuation both acting to open it, with nothing to close it.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Bash valves are not widely used in steam engines, although they are known.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Most examples were applied to some form of uniflow steam engine; unlike the more common slide and piston-valved engines with their bidirectional-flow ports, uniflow engines use inlet ports at the cylinder ends and an exhaust near the centre.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Although the opening time of a bash valve is fixed, imprecisely controlled and always occurs near top dead centre, this is not a major drawback for a steam engine.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] A more important requirement is the ability to accurately control the closing time of the valve, and for its duration to be adjustable in order to 'drive' the engine, according to varying load.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Some designs of uniflow engine have used a combined mechanical and electromagnetic valve to do this.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The valve is opened mechanically, then held by an electromagnet.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] This requires less electrical power to merely hold the valve than to open it.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] A patent for such an engine was granted to Sturtevant in 1968.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The same idea has recently been revived as the main feature of an Advanced Uniflow Steam Engine.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] In this engine, a second valve is used for exhaust purposes in the later part of the cycle too, although this one is bashed shut, rather than opened.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Bash valves have also been used for the *ad hoc* conversion of commonplace petrol small engines, such as lawnmowers, into hobbyist steam engines.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The original petrol engine sparkplug mounting hole is used as the location for a new piston-actuated bash valve, together with the original exhaust valve.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Performance and efficiency are not a need of such projects.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] One successful application for bash valves has been to pneumatic motors.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Owing to the characteristics of compressed air pneumatic power, their simplicity is valuable and their inefficiencies with other fluids are less important.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Compressed air is supplied cold to the motor.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Energy is represented solely by the pressure of the air not, unlike steam, by the combination of pressure and temperature.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Efficient operation of a steam engine relies upon expansion of the steam during the piston stroke, which relies upon accurate valve timing and an early closure of the valve.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] During the expansion phase of the steam it does not expand in a simple isothermal fashion, but does so adiabatically, much of the energy having been supplied as heat rather than pressure.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The compressed air motor is thermodynamically simpler.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] This means that expansion is less important, valve timings are thus longer and less crucial and so a simple valve may be adequate.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] To provide long opening times, the bash valve normally incorporates some form of tappet mechanism.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Rather than a valve that is held open by the piston directly, the valve becomes double-acting and is opened by the piston's impact at one end of the stroke and closed by a further impact at the other end of the stroke.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The tappet and valve are commonly separate, allowing the valve to remain in a well-defined fully open position throughout the stroke, however the tappet is bounced around by the piston.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Where a reciprocating action is produced, such as for a rock drill, the valve may be actuated either by inertia of the frame or by the movement of the working piston.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] As the piston hammers back and forth, it impacts a small tappet, which in turn moves the air valve and so reverses the flow of air to the piston.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] One form of this, the arc tappet valve, was an important feature of the Ingersoll rock drill, the first successful compressed air rock drill for use in mining and tunneling.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] This used a valve that rotated in a slight arc, rather than sliding.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The valve was double-acting, controlling the air supply for both the power and the return stroke.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The innovation that made this valve so reliable, thus successful, was a separate tappet that was actuated by the piston in passing at the middle of the stroke, rather than being hammered by a jarring direct impact of the piston.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The mid-stroke actuation also opened the valve passageways earlier, before top dead centre, allowing in air that provided a cushioning effect.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] This further improved the action of the drill, giving a powerful stroke on the working piston and drill rod, but with less damaging hammering to the frame of the drill.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Bash valves are not used in such engines.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The cylinder peak pressures of an Otto cycle engine are too high for such a valve to remain on its seat.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Bash valves are also used in a 'single-shot' situation, where a valve is opened once and then remains open until the contents of a pressure vessel are released.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] Such valves are used in some fire extinguishers and pre-charged air rifles.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] These valves are arranged so that once lifted off their seat, pressure underneath the valve becomes sufficient to keep the valve raised and so it remains open until the pressure reservoir is empty.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/bash-valve] The valve is then closed by a light spring.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The **cylinder** is the power-producing element of the steam engine powering a steam locomotive.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The cylinder is made pressure-tight with end covers and a piston; a valve distributes the steam to the ends of the cylinder.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] Cylinders were initially cast iron, but later made of steel.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The cylinder casting includes other features such as (in the case of Stephenson's Rocket) valve ports and mounting feet.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The last big American locomotives incorporated the cylinders as part of huge one-piece steel castings that were the main frame of the locomotive.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] Renewable wearing surfaces were needed inside the cylinders and provided by cast-iron bushings.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The way the valve controlled the steam entering and leaving the cylinder was known as steam distribution and shown by the shape of the indicator diagram.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] What happened to the steam inside the cylinder was assessed separately from what happened in the boiler and how much friction the moving machinery had to cope with.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] This assessment was known as "engine performance" or "cylinder performance".
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The cylinder performance, together with the boiler and machinery performance, established the efficiency of the complete locomotive.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The pressure of the steam in the cylinder was measured as the piston moved and the power moving the piston was calculated and known as cylinder power.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The forces produced in the cylinder moved the train but were also damaging to the structure which held the cylinders in place.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] Bolted joints came loose, cylinder castings and frames cracked and reduced the availability of the locomotive.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] Cylinders may be arranged in several different ways.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] On early locomotives, such as *Puffing Billy*, the cylinders were often set vertically and the motion was transmitted through beams, as in a beam engine.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The next stage, for example *Stephenson's Rocket*, was to drive the wheels directly from steeply inclined cylinders placed at the back of the locomotive.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] Direct drive became the standard arrangement, but the cylinders were moved to the front and placed either horizontal or nearly horizontal.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The front-mounted cylinders could be placed either inside (between the frames) or outside.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] In the 19th and early 20th centuries, inside cylinders were widely used in the United Kingdom, but outside cylinders were more common in Continental Europe and the United States due to their larger loading gauge.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] From about 1920, outside cylinders became more common in the UK but many inside-cylinder engines continued to be built.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] Inside cylinders give a more stable ride with less yaw or "nosing", but access for maintenance is more difficult.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] Some designers used inside cylinders for aesthetic reasons.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The demand for more power led to the development of engines with three cylinders (two outside and one inside) or four cylinders (two outside and two inside).
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] On a two-cylinder engine the cranks, whether inside or outside, are set at 90 degrees.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] As the cylinders are double-acting (i.e. fed with steam alternately at each end) this gives four impulses per revolution and ensures that there are no dead centres.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The **valve chests** or **steam chests** which contain the slide valves or piston valves may be located in various positions.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] If the cylinders are small, the valve chests may be located between the cylinders.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] For larger cylinders the valve chests are usually on top of the cylinders but, in early locomotives, they were sometimes underneath the cylinders.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The valve chests are usually on top of the cylinders but, in older locomotives, the valve chests were sometimes located alongside the cylinders and inserted through slots in the frames.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] This meant that, while the cylinders were outside, the valves were inside and could be driven by inside valve gear.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] There are many variations in the location of the valve gear.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] In British practice, inside valve gear is usually of the Stephenson type while outside valve gear is usually of the Walschaerts type.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] However, this is not a rigid rule and most types of valve gear are capable of being used either inside or outside.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] Joy valve gear was once popular, e.g. on the LNWR G Class.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] On inside-cylinder engines the valve gear is nearly always inside (between the frames), e.g.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] On some locomotives the valve gear is located outside the frames, e.g.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] There are many other variations, e.g. geared steam locomotives which may have only one cylinder.
[src:cylinder-locomotive/cylinder-locomotive] The only conventional steam locomotive with one cylinder that is known is the Nielson One-Cylinder Locomotive.
